[
    {
        "content": "<p>in a comment on <a href=\"https://github.com/roc-lang/roc/pull/5415\">https://github.com/roc-lang/roc/pull/5415</a> <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"343810\">@Brendan Hansknecht</span> <a href=\"https://github.com/roc-lang/roc/pull/5415#issuecomment-1549986120\">wrote</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This feels quite strange to enable given we don't allow shadowing in general.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I had the same reaction. I wonder if we should consider tweaking the syntax to make it clearer that it's a field name? For example, maybe:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"LiveScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"42\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nf\">number: &lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 358833553,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684266548
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the <code>: &lt;-</code> looks a bit odd to me (so maybe there's a better way to convey \"this is special\")</p>",
        "id": 358833623,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684266571
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but as soon as I see <code>number:</code> there, I immediately no longer think \"wait, that's shadowing\" - and, arguably more importantly, I no longer might think that <code>raw: number</code> might actually refer to the <code>number:</code> in the record - which, in the absence of the <code>:</code> after <code>number:</code> would be a potentially easy mistake to make</p>",
        "id": 358833844,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684266637
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, that clarifies my confusion when looking at the syntax.</p>",
        "id": 358836846,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684267371
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Interesting. Did you have that reaction because it looks like backpassing?</p>",
        "id": 358851758,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684272869
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I had the same reaction. It looked like backpassing. With the colons however it is more obvious it makes record fields</p>",
        "id": 358852017,
        "sender_full_name": "Kilian Vounckx",
        "timestamp": 1684272985
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As an aside. I'm really looking forward to using this feature. Especially in combination with the Parser example</p>",
        "id": 358852117,
        "sender_full_name": "Kilian Vounckx",
        "timestamp": 1684273026
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't love the <code>: &lt;-</code> syntax because it makes the <code>&lt;-</code> look like it's part of the expression, and someone might think you can do this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nf\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">parse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 358852663,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684273230
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not sure on the syntax either, however with only the arrow, I didn't get what it meant. With the colon I got it immediately. I think that by using it I would understand it eventually as well, but with the colon I understood just by looking</p>",
        "id": 358853153,
        "sender_full_name": "Kilian Vounckx",
        "timestamp": 1684273446
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How I see it is that backpassing reads as a weird way to write <code>=</code>.</p>\n<p>these two feel equivalent</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">someFunc</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">3</span>\n<span class=\"nx\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">someAwaitedFunc</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">3</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>So when I read the current syntax it goes from:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>To essentially:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>So it really feels like raw is getting set to the parsed number, not the original number.<br>\nOf course that is the wrong reading of the syntax, but it matches the rough rule of thumb that is gained from working with backpassing.</p>",
        "id": 358855191,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684274336
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Adding the <code>:</code>, though ugly, makes it immediately clear that we are setting a record field. The only place you would see <code>number: someExpression</code> is when setting a record field.</p>",
        "id": 358855387,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684274426
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't know the best syntax, cause if you proced to apply my rough rule of thumb to the proposed syntax, it goes from:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>to:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">number:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Which is fundamentally just a broken syntax.</p>",
        "id": 358855502,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684274498
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see your point. That said, I think people are unlikely to write code like this. I just came up with that example to test the canonicalizer.</p>",
        "id": 358855711,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684274579
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What do you think about this point <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"343810\">@Brendan Hansknecht</span> ?<br>\n<span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"489294\">Agus Zubiaga</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/304641-ideas/topic/label.20syntax.20for.20record.20builders/near/358852663\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I don't love the <code>: &lt;-</code> syntax because it makes the <code>&lt;-</code> look like it's part of the expression, and someone might think you can do this:</p>\n<p><div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nf\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">parse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div><br>\n</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 358855885,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684274656
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Aside, this code:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>actually makes total sense to me even if we don't want to support it.<br>\nIt would be saying, applicatively run <code>parse number</code> multiply it by 2 and then store it in the number record field.<br>\nIt feels like it would be a syntax for anonymous backpassing.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nx\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">Stdin</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"nx\">getInt</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">Task</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"nx\">await</span>\n<span class=\"nv\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\"># could be with anonymous backpassing</span>\n\n<span class=\"nv\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">Stdin</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"nx\">getInt</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">|&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">Task</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"nx\">await</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Not saying we should at all try to support it, just saying that it is immediately what I think when reading it.</p>",
        "id": 358855996,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684274721
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think we just can't support that syntax. Sure it works in that example, but as soon as you wrap <code>(&lt;- ...)</code> in a function we would desugar to the wrong thing</p>",
        "id": 358856174,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684274800
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Can you give an example?</p>",
        "id": 358856224,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684274827
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's unclear what this should desugar to</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Elm\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"nf\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">fn</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"nf\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">parse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"p\">)</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 358856504,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684274969
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Why?<br>\n<code>2 * (&lt;- parse number)</code> is really just <code>Num.multiply 2 (&lt;- parse number)</code></p>",
        "id": 358856676,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684275047
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This syntax would just need to have priority to resolve before running the function.</p>",
        "id": 358856732,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684275079
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>True. I guess it also applies there. I just think in a world where you can do <code>(&lt;- ...)</code>, it doesn't make sense to limit it to records. But if you don't, the compiler wouldn't know where to apply the function on the RHS of <code>&lt;-</code>.</p>",
        "id": 358856871,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684275133
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Very true.</p>",
        "id": 358856905,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684275151
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not to mention it'd be a parsing nightmare</p>",
        "id": 358856926,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684275166
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Anyway, I think this is a digression. Let's just assume that syntax isn't supported.</p>",
        "id": 358856941,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684275174
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes</p>",
        "id": 358856959,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684275182
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What if instead of <code>&lt;-</code> we used something like <code>:=</code>?</p>",
        "id": 358857010,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684275206
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That sounds fine, though maybe a bit less clear/more subtle (not sure if that is an issue or not).</p>",
        "id": 358857124,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684275251
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'd like to use a symbol without a space in the middle, to make it look like it's a special kind of assignment, not that it's part of the expression</p>",
        "id": 358857146,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684275261
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So we get:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"42\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>hmm....maybe that doesn't work. <code>:=</code> feels too much like an assignment and again like <code>raw</code> would be getting set to the parsed number.</p>",
        "id": 358857283,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684275343
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think making it look like an assignment may specifically be the issue here.</p>",
        "id": 358857383,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684275385
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I mean, we could set <code>raw</code> to the parsed number. Not that you'd ever want that.</p>",
        "id": 358857398,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684275396
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So I think the space is good in this case.</p>",
        "id": 358857399,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684275396
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>:&lt;</code> lol</p>",
        "id": 358857590,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684275510
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"343810\">Brendan Hansknecht</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/304641-ideas/topic/label.20syntax.20for.20record.20builders/near/358857383\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think making it look like an assignment may specifically be the issue here.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I do think about it as a kind of assignment though.</p>",
        "id": 358857620,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684275536
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I mean field assignment</p>",
        "id": 358857698,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684275588
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Not a random def in the middle of a record</p>",
        "id": 358857758,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684275604
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>\\* making it look too much like an assignment outside of a record, which in my mind are <code>x =</code> and <code>x &lt;-</code>.</p>",
        "id": 358857851,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684275645
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yeah <code>:&lt;</code> or something a bit strange in general may work too.</p>",
        "id": 358857975,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684275721
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, I think I would prefer <code>: &lt;-</code>to that. Something about <code>&lt;-</code> really says \"effectful assignment\" for me.</p>",
        "id": 358860447,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684276992
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>which since we're inside of a record, it can only be field assignment, so I personally don't think <code>:</code> is required</p>",
        "id": 358861023,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684277281
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I can see how someone might confuse it with backpassing, but to use Record Builders you already have to learn a new syntax</p>",
        "id": 358861340,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684277421
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If we block using the same name, i think it is a great syntax</p>",
        "id": 358861583,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684277565
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think it reads really confusingly of we don't</p>",
        "id": 358861613,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684277581
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>by that do you mean erroring on <code>number &lt;- ...</code> or on <code>raw : number</code>? I guess the former</p>",
        "id": 358861928,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684277759
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'd be happy with that compromise</p>",
        "id": 358862212,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684277916
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I like <code>&lt;-</code> and I don't see myself writing code like the example in my PR</p>",
        "id": 358862252,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684277941
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Erroring on a variable named <code>number</code> existing in the same scope as a recorder builder <code>{ number &lt;- ... }</code></p>\n<p>So would need to be:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">numberStr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"42\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">numberStr</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">Raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">numberStr</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 358862297,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684277965
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Gotcha. Yeah, I think that's the best option. Basically reverting my PR.</p>",
        "id": 358862343,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684277996
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Though also probably we be fine to block it from other record fields or some other solution that avoid the duplicate name and potential confusion on variable vs field.</p>",
        "id": 358862427,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684278021
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Something like this?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"42\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\">#     ^ ambiguous var error</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 358862671,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684278127
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah</p>",
        "id": 358862843,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684278233
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, actually I really like that form of error message cause:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>I think it will very very rarely come up in practice</li>\n<li>In many cases, it should be fixable by reordering fields</li>\n<li>When it isn't you just need to rename one value</li>\n</ol>\n<p>This could be a valid fix for example.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"42\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parse</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 358865288,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1684279757
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>even setting aside the shadowing concern, the thing I like about <code>number:</code> is that it's more obvious that it's making record fields. For example:</p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"497765\">Kilian Vounckx</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/304641-ideas/topic/label.20syntax.20for.20record.20builders/near/358852017\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I had the same reaction. It looked like backpassing. With the colons however it is more obvious it makes record fields</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 358865483,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684279896
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>honestly I think that makes it worth exploring in its own right, shadowing concerns aside <span aria-label=\"big smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f604\" role=\"img\" title=\"big smile\">:big_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 358865496,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684279911
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(I also don't love how <code>number: &lt;-</code> looks though - I just think it's worth continuing to try out alternatives!)</p>",
        "id": 358865559,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684279936
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>a possible direction: since each of these need a <code>Task.batch</code>, we could put a special operator after that</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"42\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">Task</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"nx\">batch</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseNum</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">string</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">Task</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"nx\">batch</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseStr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">string</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 358866651,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684280601
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>not saying <code>|</code> specifically is the best one, but the general idea is that <code>[field]: [expr] [symbol] [expr]</code> becomes the syntax that lets you know it's a record builder</p>",
        "id": 358866759,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684280657
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so it would be coupled to record syntax only; you couldn't use that special symbol just anywhere</p>",
        "id": 358866789,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684280689
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>only after the expression following the <code>:</code> in a record literal field label</p>",
        "id": 358866818,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684280714
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>that does kinda share the same concern about <code>number: &lt;-</code> though, which is that it kinda suggests <code>&lt;-</code> might be usable anywhere</p>",
        "id": 358866868,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684280752
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You don't necessarily need a <code>Task.batch</code> though. In my example, <code>parse</code> does both <code>apply</code> and construct the parser. Some applicative libs such as <code>NoRedInk/elm-json-decode-pipeline</code> and<code>elm/parser</code> use this pattern.</p>",
        "id": 358867010,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684280842
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>ah true</p>",
        "id": 358867125,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684280910
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>here's an idea I don't like, but which I'll put out there anyway just to get it out of my head:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"42\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">number:</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseNum</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">string:</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseStr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">string</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 358867958,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684281598
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Here's an idea I don't know if I like:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">apply</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseNum</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">string</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">apply</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseStr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">string</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p><code>apply</code> being a reserved keyword</p>",
        "id": 358868279,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684281724
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>does this make any sense? <span aria-label=\"thinking\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f914\" role=\"img\" title=\"thinking\">:thinking:</span> </p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"42\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseNum</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">string</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseStr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">string</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 358868490,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684281894
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so same as this, but flipped:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"42\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseNum</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">string</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseStr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">string</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 358868620,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684281982
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think it makes less sense than <code>: &lt;-</code> but it does look more visually pleasing</p>",
        "id": 358868623,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684281988
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>hm, I think <code>number: &lt;-</code> actually might be a parsing ambiguity  <span aria-label=\"sweat smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f605\" role=\"img\" title=\"sweat smile\">:sweat_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 358868783,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282089
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh nm</p>",
        "id": 358868829,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282122
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it's fine because backpassing always requires a pattern to the left</p>",
        "id": 358868838,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282139
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseNum</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>is kinda growing on me <span aria-label=\"big smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f604\" role=\"img\" title=\"big smile\">:big_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 358868872,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282171
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, I can get used to it</p>",
        "id": 358868961,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684282211
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I like that I can always tell these apart without further context:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseNum</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\"># always record builder</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">&lt;-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseNum</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\"># always backpassing</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 358868972,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282227
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I just feel like people are going to try <code>(&lt;- parseNum number, &lt;- parseStr str)</code> and be disappointed</p>",
        "id": 358869030,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684282271
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it's possible, although that's one of those things we can always verify experimentally</p>",
        "id": 358869044,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282292
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if it turns out to be a significant problem in practice, we can revisit</p>",
        "id": 358869061,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282316
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>which sounds reasonable to me, considering <code>number: &lt;-</code> does solve a couple of existing known pain points mentioned in this thread (shadowing concern, not realizing that <code>number &lt;-</code> was going into a record field)</p>",
        "id": 358869160,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282359
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>and it's uncharted syntax territory anyway, so it's not like we can just fall back on a syntax another language uses for this <span aria-label=\"sweat smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f605\" role=\"img\" title=\"sweat smile\">:sweat_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 358869196,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282385
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Apparently, Idris has a <a href=\"https://idris2.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorial/interfaces.html#notation\"><code>!</code>-notation</a> which is like <code>&lt;-</code> but you can put it anywhere</p>",
        "id": 358869231,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684282422
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>whaaaat</p>",
        "id": 358869342,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282477
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I need to overcome my shock at choosing to have <code>!x</code> mean something completely unrelated to negation and read how this works</p>",
        "id": 358869440,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282553
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh I see</p>",
        "id": 358869675,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282684
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Actually, I guess that's for sequential stuff. For applicatives, there's <a href=\"https://idris2.readthedocs.io/en/latest/tutorial/interfaces.html#idiom-brackets\">Idiom brackets</a>.</p>",
        "id": 358869788,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684282768
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yeah so we couldn't do this because it relies on higher-kinded types to know what <code>bind</code> (or <code>apply</code>) and <code>pure</code> (or <code>suceced</code>) are</p>",
        "id": 358869789,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282769
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yup</p>",
        "id": 358869800,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684282783
    },
    {
        "content": "<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"CoffeeScript\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s\">\"42\"</span>\n\n<span class=\"nx\">succeed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">raw</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"p\">,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">number</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"o\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseNum</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">number</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">|</span><span class=\"p\">],</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"nv\">string</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"o\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">parseStr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nx\">string</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">|</span><span class=\"p\">],</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Yeah, I don't like that <span aria-label=\"upside down\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f643\" role=\"img\" title=\"upside down\">:upside_down:</span></p>",
        "id": 358869996,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684282902
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>how do you feel about trying <code>number: &lt;-</code> and seeing how it feels in practice? if it was a standalone PR, we could revert back to the current syntax if it ends up seeming worse in practice</p>",
        "id": 358870079,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282931
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, let's do that</p>",
        "id": 358870120,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684282959
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There can be 0 or more spaces between <code>:</code> and <code>&lt;-</code>, right?</p>",
        "id": 358870169,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684282986
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yeah</p>",
        "id": 358870177,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684282994
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>cool</p>",
        "id": 358870215,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684283024
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't mind <code>number &lt;-</code>.</p>\n<p><code>x &lt;- Stdin.getInt |&gt; Task.await</code> looks like variable assignment because it shows up in contexts that look like you should be doing variable assignment.<br>\n<code>number &lt;- parseNumber numberStr</code> looks like field assignment because you do it inside <code>{}</code>, where you assign record fields.</p>\n<p>It's as much an issue with shadowing as this case:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span><code>number = 42\nr = {\n  number: 41,\n  biggerNumber: number,\n}\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>There are already rules about how <code>field &lt;-</code> isn't assigning a value you can use in future calculations.</p>",
        "id": 358870289,
        "sender_full_name": "Sky Rose",
        "timestamp": 1684283052
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think it's worth trying the other way to see if people get used to it</p>",
        "id": 358870394,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684283134
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think it's plausible that either could work, but I definitely think <code>number:</code> is clearer that it's a field label - you don't even need any context to infer it <span aria-label=\"big smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f604\" role=\"img\" title=\"big smile\">:big_smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 358870437,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1684283162
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I updated the parser to the new syntax and it seems to be working fine. I need to leave now but I will work on the formatter tomorrow and make a PR!</p>",
        "id": 358882956,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684290674
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>fwiw I had the same confusion when seeing the previous syntax, I immediately thought that ordering would be a problem since we could in theory create dependencies between parallel requests for instance (bc I also thought of ordered assignments)</p>\n<p>the new syntax with <code>: &lt;-</code> seems to solve it imo, we might experiment stuff but I think the less syntax we add the to language the better and this one adds no new special operators.</p>",
        "id": 358922821,
        "sender_full_name": "Georges Boris",
        "timestamp": 1684312632
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it should be easy to throw meaningful error messages if the user tries to <code>(&lt;- fn x)</code>, right? \"it looks like you're trying to use backpassing in an unsupported place. these are the only two supported ways of using backpassing in Roc: ...\"</p>",
        "id": 358923478,
        "sender_full_name": "Georges Boris",
        "timestamp": 1684312820
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Eating lunch by myself today, so I decided to <a href=\"#narrow/stream/316715-contributing/topic/Pull.20Request.20for.20Review/near/359041931\">wrap this up</a></p>",
        "id": 359042584,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1684344920
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>delicious!</p>",
